===Verb===
{{en-verb|env|ies}}

# {{label|en|transitive}} To feel displeasure or hatred towards (someone) for their good fortune or possessions. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
# {{label|en|obsolete|intransitive}} To have [[envious]] feelings (at). {{defdate|15th-18th c.}}
#* {{RQ:RBrtn AntmyMlncly}}, II.3.3:
#*: I do not '''envy''' at their wealth, titles, offices;{{...}}let me live quiet and at ease.
#* Jeremy Taylor:
#*: Who would '''envy''' at the prosperity of the wicked?
# {{label|en|obsolete|transitive}} To give (something) to (someone) [[grudgingly]] or [[reluctantly]]; to [[begrudge]]. {{defdate|16th-18th c.}}
#* '''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', III.v:
#*: But that sweet Cordiall, which can restore / A loue-sick hart, she did to him '''enuy'''&nbsp;[…].
# {{label|en|obsolete}} To show [[malice]] or ill will; to [[rail]].
#* Shakespeare:
#: He has{{...}}'''envied''' against the people.
# {{label|en|obsolete}} To do harm to; to injure; to disparage.
#* J. Fletcher
#*: If I make a lie / To gain your love and '''envy''' my best mistress, / Put me against a wall.
# {{label|en|obsolete}} To hate.
#: {{rfquotek|Marlowe}}
# {{label|en|obsolete}} To [[emulate]].
#: {{rfquotek|Spenser}}

